WE THEN SWEPT UP QUICK DRY AND PLACED IN A PLASTIC BAG. (THE SHIPMENT WOULD BE SAFER IF SHIPPED ON PALLETS WHEN IN THESE PLASTIC DRUMS).

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS MAKING A DELIVERY OF GASOLINE AT THE SHELL STATION IN HUDSON, MICHIGAN.  WHEN THE DRIVER ARRIVED AND WAS IN POSITION FOR THE DELIVERY, HE OPENED ALL OF THE FIRE VALVES ON THE TRANSPORT TRAILER, ALLOWING THE GASOLINE ON BOARD TO FLOW INTO EACH OF THE FIVE INDIVIDUAL DELIVERY TUBES, TO EACH OF THE FIVE INDIVIDUAL UNLOADING VALVES.  THE #5 UNLOADING VALVE (BUTTERFLY TYPE) WAS NOT CLOSED ALL THE WAY AND WHEN THE DRIVER REMOVED THE DUST CAP FROM THIS UNLOADING VALVE, TO ENABLE HIM TO HOOK UP HIS DELIVERY HOSE TO IT, THE GASOLINE GUSHED OUT OF THE UNLOADING VALVE AND KNOCKED HIM TO THE GROUND.  THE DRIVER THEN SHUT DOWN ALL THE FIRE VALVES, AS QUICKLY AS POSSIBLE, TO STOP THE FLOW OF GASOLINE FROM ALL COMPARTMENTS.  THE DRIVERS HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO DO INSPECTIONS OF ALL THE VALVES ON THE TRAILERS, BEFORE LOADING, TO HELP INSURE THAT THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT WOULD NOT OCCUR AGAIN.  PLEASE SEE ATTACHED SHEET, FOR ADDITIONAL INFORMATION.

column168: OUR VEHICLE WAS SCHEDULED FOR A GASOLINE DELIVERY TO TURKEY HILL STORE #176 HONEY BROOK, PA.  DRIVER STOPPED AT WRONG LOCATION (STORE #71 HONEY BROOK, PA.).  DRIVER TOOK STICK READING BUT DID NOT CHECK WITH THE STORE MANAGER TO CONFIRM THAT HE WAS AT RIGHT LOCATION AND ALSO TO MAKE SURE DELIVERY WOULD FIT.  TANK FILLED UP AND APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS WAS RELEASED ON PROPERTY.  NATIONAL RESPONSE, FIRE DEPARTMENT AND STATE EMERGENCY RESPONSE WERE NOTIFIED.

UPON OPENING THE TRAILER A CARTON TIPPED OVER IN THE TRAILER AND MATERIAL WAS LEAKING ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE CARTON WAS TIPPED UPRIGHT, OIL DRY AND BAKING SODA WERE PLACED ON THE SPILLED MATERIAL.  THE BOX WAS THEN PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM LINER.  THEN INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  THE MATERIAL WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  THE LOADING TERMINAL WAS NOTIFIED OF THE IMPROPER LOADING.

PRINCIPAL CAUSE OF DISCHARGE WAS OPERATOR NEGLIGENCE.  DRIVER LOADED BEYOND TRAILER CAPACITY AND TWENTY GALLONS OF PETROLEUM CRUDE OIL ESCAPED THE CONTAINER, FLOWING FROM THE DOME HATCH DOWN THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER. TRANSPORT-TRUCK WAS STATIONARY AND LOADING FROM AN OIL FIELD PRODUCTION FACILITY.  LOADING AREA SURFACE CONSISTED OF HARD-PACKED DIRT.  AN AREA 3 FEET BY 6 FEET WAS STAINED.  CLEAN-UP WAS ACCOMPLISHED WITH ABSORBENTS AND SURFACE GRADING.  OPERATOR WAS PROPERLY IN ATTENDANCE DURING CARGO TRANSFER AND SHUT DOWN THE LOADING OPERATION.  HE WAS ADVISED TO BE MORE ALERT TO TRAILER CAPACITY.

column168: THE INCIDENT OCCURRED AT APPROXIMATELY 11:50 A.M. ON AUGUST 8, 1990. THE MA TERIAL, DESCRIBED AS SPENT NITRIC ACID, LESS THAN 40%, WAS BEING PICKED UP FROM PHASE II OF 1229 MONTGOMERY AVE., SAN BRUNO, CA 94066 (SEE ENCLOSED MA NIFEST NO. 88331732.) AS GREAT WESTERN'S EMPLOYEE, KEITH MYERS WAS TRANSFER RING THE PRODUCT FROM PHASE II'S FORKLIFT TO THE GREAT WESTERN TRUCK, THE D RUM RUPTURED, SPILLING THE CONTENTS (APPROXIMATELY 53 GALLONS) ONTO THE TRU CK AND THE STREET. MR. MYERS IMMEDIATELY BLOCKED NEARBY STORM DRAINS TO PRE VENT FURTHER SPREAD OF THE CONTAMINANTS. PHASE II NOTIFIED THE SAN BRUNO FI RE DEPARTMENT AND THE SAN MATEO COUNTY DOHS. GREAT WESTERN BROUGHT IN A RES PONSE TEAM FROM CROSBY AND OVERTON TO ASSIST IN THE CLEANUP OPERATION. THE CLEANUP OPERATION CONSISTED OF ABSORBING OF THE LIQUID PORTION OF THE S PILL AND STEAM CLEANING OF APPROXIMATELY 100 FEET OF MONTGOMERY AVENUE. THE RESULTING WASTE WAS PROPERLY HANDLED AND DISPOSED OF BY CROSBY AND OVERTON (SEE ENCLOSED MANIFEST NOS. 89728234 AND 89728233.) THE CLEANUP OPERATION WAS SUPERVISED AND APPROVED BY DENNIS A. FRANKS OF SAN MATEO COUNTY DOHS. THERE WERE NO INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS INCIDENT AND THERE WERE MINIMAL HAZARDS TO HUMAN HEALTH AND THE ENVIRONMENT.

WHEN HE OPENED THE DOOR HE NOTICED THAT THE CONTENTS OF THE CARTON WERE LEAKING OUT ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR AND CALLED IMMEDIATELY FOR INSTRUCTIONS.  USING STAY DRY MATERIAL, HE SURROUNDED THE CONTAINER TO PREVENT LEAKAGE.  THIS MATERIAL COMPLETELY ABSORBED THE SPILL.  ALL OF THE MATERIALS WERE PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM.

DRIVER NOTICED AN ODOR AND LIQUID LEAKING FROM HIS TRAILER AND CONTACTED THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT.  CHEMTREC WAS CALLED.  DISPOSAL CONTROL SERVICES WAS CONTRACTED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM AND ALL CLEAN UP MATERIALS WERE SEALED INSIDE A SEPARATE DRUM AND SHIPPED ONTO DESTINATION.
BOX FELL FROM SKID AND BURST ON CONTACT.  THE AREA WAS ISOLATED AND THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED WITH OIL DRY.  THE PRODUCT EVAPORATED AND THE CONTAMINATED CLEAN UP MATERIALS WERE DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.

DOCK WORKER DISCOVERED ONE CARTON THAT HAD BEEN DAMAGED BY OTHER FREIGHT AND WAS LEAKING.  AREA WAS SECURED AND THE MATERIAL IDENTIFIED.  CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED.  LEAKING MATERIAL WAS PLACED INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM ALONG WITH TWO OTHER CARTONS THAT HAD BEEN SOAKED WITH THE MATERIAL AND IS BEING HELD FOR DISPOSAL.

WHEN TRAILER WAS OPENED AT TERMINAL, TWO DOCK WORKERS NOTICED A PUNGENT ODOR IN THE TRAILER.  THE SHIPPER AND LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE CONTACTED. DUE TO THE AMOUNT OF MATERIAL LOADED ON THE VEHICLE AND THE POTENTIAL HAZARDS INVOLVED. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT TOOK CONTROL OF THE SCENE AND ORDERED AN EVACUATION OF THE ROADWAY TERMINAL AND A NUMBER OF NEIGHBORING BUSINESSES.  AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM FROM CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT UNLOADED THE  TRAILER.  A SMALL LEAK WAS DISCOVERED FROM THE LID OF A FIVE GALLON PAIL.  APPARENTLY, THE PAIL WAS OVERFILLED AND THE LIQUID MATERIAL INSIDE EXPANDED IN THE HEAT AND SEEPED OUT.  TWO DOCK WORKERS WERE TAKEN TO ST LUKE'S HOSPITAL FOR OBSERVATION AND RELEASED.  NO TREATMENT WAS GIVEN AND NO TIME WAS LOST FROM WORK.  APPROXIMATELY 1,000 PEOPLE WERE EVACUATED FROM NEARBY BUSINESSES THROUGHOUT THE DAY.

column168: SUBSTANCE WAS ENCOUNTERED DURING NORMAL OPERATIONS. UPON OPENING TRAILER DOOR TO COMMENCE UNLOADING, STRONG AMMONIA ODOR EXISTED. LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CONTACTED TO COORDINATE REMOVAL. IN THE FUTURE, ALL LOADS WHICH ARE SUSPECTED TO BE CONTAMINATED BY HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WILL BE MOVED AWAY FROM UNPROTECTED PERSONNEL AND ATTENDED TO BY A PROPERLY OUTFITTED AND TRAINED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL REMOVAL ORGANIZATION. VIBRATION FROM TRANSIT IS A MAJOR CONTRIBUTOR TO SPILLS. ALL HAZARDOUS LIQUIDS SHOULD BE CONTAINED IN A MANNE R IN WHICH THE CAP OR LID IS UNAFFECTED BY VIBRATION BY BEING WIRED OR LOCKED IN SOME SIMPLE WAY.

column168: ON SATURDAY, AUGUST 18, 1990, AT 1800 HOURS, THE CAR INSPECTORS SPOTTED TANK CAR UTLX 200545 LEAKING FROM AROUND THE FITTINGS ON TOP OF THE TANK CAR WHILE IT WAS BEING MOVED BY A YARD CREW.  THE LEAKING TANK CAR WAS REPORTED TO THE YARDMASTER AND THE CAR WAS PLACED IN THE CAB TRACK.  THE YARDMASTER CONTACTED MR. T W. GRUBBS, SUPERVISOR POLICE AND SAFETY, AT 1815 HOURS BY RADIO, AND HE ARRIVED AT THE TANK CAR AT 1840 HOURS.  MR GRUBBS MADE AN INSPECTION OF THE TANK CAR AND FOUND IT WAS NOT LEAKING ON HIS SRRIVAL, BUT HAD BEEN LEAKING WHEN IN MOTION FROM AROUND THE AREA OF THE FITTINGS WHICH CONTAINED THE SAFETY PRESSURE DISC.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AT 1925 HOURS AND THEY, IN TRUN, NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER, DEGUSSA CORPORATION OF THEODORE, ALABAMA.  ALSO, THE AAR'S BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES WAS NOTIFIED AND THEY CONTACTED WILLIAM J OERTLY, JR., DISTRICT INSPECTOR. AT 1940 HOURS, CALVIN DIXON, SAFETY COORDINATOR FOR DEGUSSA CORPORATION, CALLED AND WAS ADVISED OF THE SITUATION.  MR. DIXON ADVISED HE WOULD CONTACT HIS PEOPLE AND CALL BACK AT 2200 HOURS.  MR OERTLY CALLED AT 2055 HOURS AND ADVISED THE YARDMASTER TO HAVE MR. GRUBBS CALL HIM IF HE NEEDED ASSISTANCE WITH THE TANK CAR.  MR. GRUBBS CALLED MR. OERTLY AT 2105 HOURS AND REQUESTED HIS ASSISTANCE IN REPAIRING THE SAFETY PRESSURE DISC ON THE TANK CAR. MR. OERTLY ARRIVED AT ACCA YARD AT 2135 HOURS AND REPAIRS TO THE TANK CAR WERE BEGUN AT 2200 HOURS.  THE SAFETY PRESSURE DISC WAS REPLACED AND THE REPAIRS WERE COMPLETED AT 2218 HOURS, AT WHICH TIME THE CAR WAS PLACED BACK INTO RAIL SERVICE.  THE SHIPPER'S REPRESENTATIVE, MR. DIXON, WAS NOTIFIED THAT THE TANK CAR HAD BEEN REPAIRED AT 2240 HOURS.

MATERIALS OF RICHMOND (A CLEAN-UP COMPANY), WAS CALLED TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WASHED THE PARKING LOT AND STREET DOWN WITH WATER. column168: PER THE REQUIREMENT OF 310 CMR 40.374 (U) (RELEASES WHICH REQUIRE NOTIFICATION) , I AM WRITING TO FORMALLY NOTIFY THE DEPARTMENT OF A RELEASE FROM ONE OF OUR VEHICLES THAT OCCURRED ON AUGUST 23, 1990.  AT APPROXIMATELY 2:30 PM OUR TRANSPORTER TRAILER, #T4, (MASSACHUSETTS REGISTRATION 26726) RETURNED TO OUR FACILITY IN STOUGHTON AFTER LEAKING #4 FUEL OIL LOADED AT THE SAME FACILITY.  THE RELEASE WAS THE RESULT OF AN IMPROPER SEATING OF AN INTERNAL VENT.  THIS DEVICE IS USED TO ALLOW OUTSIDE AIR TO ENTER THE TANK WHILE THE LOAD IS BEING DISCHARGED,  THIS UNIT HAD JUST RECEIVED AN EXTENSIVE OVERHAUL AND APPARENTLY THE LINKAGE THAT CONNECTS THE VENT AND VALVE WAS OUT OF ALIGNMENT.  UPON RETURNING TO STOUGHTON, THE MECHANICS INSPECTED THIS VEHICLE AND DETERMINED THE PROBLEM.  THE MECHANICS DISCONNECTED THE LINKAGE ALLOWING THE VENT TO SEAL TIGHTLY AND NO FURTHER DISCHARGE COULD TAKE PLACE.  CLAIRE FITZGERALD, FROM STOUGHTON OPERATIONS, WAS SENT TO DETERMINE THE EXTENT OF THE SPILL ON CANTON, BROOK AND CENTRAL STREETS.  SHE COMPLETED ASSESSMENT AND CALLED FOR A CREW TO COMMENCE A CLEAN UP.  CLAIRE REPORTED THAT SHE DID NOT NOTICE ANY FREE LIQUID ON THE ROAD AND ONLY SOME STAINING.  THIS STAINING STARTED AT THE END OF JET-LINE'S DRIVEWAY ON CANTON STREET AND SPORADICALLY DOWN BROOK STREET ONTO CENTRAL STREET TO A POINT WHERE IT INTERSECTS SIMPSON STREET.  THE ESTIMATED TOTAL AMOUNT RELEASED WAS FIVE (5) TO FIFTEEN(15) GALLONS.  ON RECEIVING NOTICE OF THE RELEASE, THE FOLLOWING AGENCIES WERE IMMEDIATELY NOFIFIED: MA DEP, LAKEVILLE OFFICE, STOUGHTON FIRE DEPARTMENT, STOUGHTON HAZARDOUS WASTE COORDINATOR AND MR CHARLES STARKOWSKY.  AT APPROXIMATELY 3:15 PM LIEUTENANT FAVRETT, OF THE STOUGHTON FIRE DEPARTMENT, ARRIVED AT JET-LINE SERVICES.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT HE WOULD RETRACE THE TRUCK'S ROUTE FROM THE FACILITY.  HIS INVESTIGATION CONCURRED WITH JET-LINE'S REPORT.  THE ONLY VISIBLE EVIDENCE WAS SOME STAINING OF THE AFFECTED ROADS AND A SMALL AREA OF HEAVY STAIN AT THE END OF BROOK STREET AT THE INTERSECTION WITH CENTRAL STREET.  OUR PERSONNEL WERE DIRECTED TO LAY DOWN SPEEDY-DRY (APPROXIMATELY TEN (10) POUNDS TO ABSORB ANY PRODUCT IN THIS AREA AS A PRECAUTION.  AT APPROXIMATELY 3:25 PM , WE WERE JOINED BY REGINA MCCARTHY, OF THE STOUGHTON BOARD OF HEALTH.  WE DISCUSSED WHAT HAD OCCURRED AND WOULD FOLLOW-UP ON ANY QUESTIONS SHE RAISED.  UPON COMPLETION OF THE CLEAN-UP, LIEUTENANT FAVRETT AND I RETURNED TO STOUGHTON, INTERVIEWED THE DRIVER, MECHANICS AND DETERMINED THAT THE VEHICLE COULD PROCEED TO ITS DESTINATION.  OUR MECHANIC IN MAINE HAD BEEN INSTRUCTED TO INSPECT AND REPAIR THE INTERNAL SYSTEM ON THIS TRAILER.  I ALSO DISCUSSED THIS TRAILER WITH OUR MAIN OPERATIONS COORDINATOR AND SPECIAL ATTENTION AND INSPECTIONS WILL ACCOMPANY THIS UNIT.  ASSIGNED DRIVER WILL BE INSTRUCTED ON THIS TO AVOID ANY SUCH ACCIDENTS IN THE FUTURE.

column168: ON AUGUST 10 1990, WHILE UNLOADING 1500 GALLONS INTO A BULK TANK AT INTERNATIONAL PAPER PEORIA, IL, THE BULK TANK OVERFLOWED.  THE NEW TANK INSTALLATION HAS CONTAINMENT PITS WHERE APPROXIMATLEY 75 GALLONS OF SOLVENT WAS HELD.  THE BARTON SOLVENTS DRIVER IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THEIR SHIFT SUPERVISOR.  INTERNATIONAL PAPER PUMPED THE PIT SOLVENT INTO DRUMS WHICH WILL BE USED AS WASH UP SOLVENT.  NO SOLVENT ESCAPED FROM THE PITS, NOR PENETRATED THE GROUND.  THE ORDER WAS FOR 1500 GALLONS.  AT THE TIME OF DELIVERY THE TANK WOULD NOT HOLD 1500 GALLONS AS WERE ANTICIPATING.  THER NEW TANK FARM HAS INTERNAL SHUT-OFF VALVES TO PREVENT OVERFILLING, HOWEVER, THEY HAVE TO BE ACTIVATED BY A TIGHT HOOK UP.  THE TANKS HAVE FOUR INCH OUTLETS, OUR HOSES ARE TWO INCH, FITTING INSIDE THEIR FOUR INCH FILL PIPE FOR A GRAVITY UNLOAD.  IT WAS THIS IMPROPER CONNECTION AND NOT A PACKAGE FAILURE THAT CAUSED THIS INCIDENT.  OUR DRIVERS HAD REQUESTED INTERNATIONAL PAPER INSTALL A REDUCER COUPLING FOR DIRECT HOOKUP.  THIS IS NOW BEING DONE BY INTERNATIONAL PAPER.  THIS SHOULD PREVENT REOCCURANCE OF SPILL.

THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CLIMBED INTO THE CAB OF HIS TRUCK TO SHUT OFF HIS ENGINE AND TURN OFF THE PRODUCT PUMP.  AS THE DRIVER TURNED OFF HIS ENGINE THE FUMES FROM THE GASOLINE IGNITED.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT EXTINGUISHED THE FIRE WITH IN 30 MINUTES AND DEA WAS NOTIFIED.  CUSTOMER ORDERED 5200 GALLONS FOR A 6000 GALLON STORAGE TANK THAT HAD 1300 GALLONS IN STORAGE.

ON AUGUST 20, 1990 AT APPROXIMATELY 12:00 PM BARTON ENVIRONMENTAL INC., EXPERIENCED A SPILL AT THE ABOVE REFERENCED FACILITY.  THE SPILL WAS CREATED WHEN WASTE PAINT (TOLUENE AND MINERAL SPIRITS) FROM SHERWIN WILLIAMS WAS INADVERTENTLY LOADED ONTO A TANKER WHICH HAD HAD SODIUM HYDROXIDE FROM FORD MOTOR CO ON IT THE PREVIOUS DAY. THE TWO MINERALS WERE INCOMPATIBLE.  THE REACTION CREATED THE LIBERATION OF HYDROGEN GAS IN SUFFICIENT QUANTITIES TO OVERLOAD THE VENTING SYSTEM ON THE TANKER RESULTING IN SHEERING OF THE SHEER PINS ON THE REAR DOME OF THE TANKER. UPON SHEERING THE DOME OPENED, AS RESULT OF THE PRESSURE INSIDE THE TANKER, LITERALLY SPEWING APPROXIMATELY 1500 TO 2000 GALLONS OF THE PAINT/SODIUM HYDROXIDE MIXTURE ON THE GROUND.  THE SPILL CONTAMINATED SEVERAL VEHICLES, THE PARKING LOT AND THE ADJACENT CAPER ROAD RIGHT OF WAY.  THE REACTION BETWEEN THE TWO MATERIALS CONTINUED FOR SEVERAL HOURS DELAYING IMMEDIATE CLEAN UP OF THE MATERIAL.  AT APPROXIMATELY 3:30 PM CLEAN UP ACTIVITIES COMMENCED.

column168: TRUCK WAS NEARLY UNLOADED WHEN THE SAFETY VENT MANFUNCTIONED AND THE PRESSURE PUSHED OUT TIGHTFIT CONNECTION OUT OF THE FILL PIPE. DRIVER WAS REQUIRED BY RECEIVER TO SUPPLY EXTRA LENGTHS OF HOSE AND A DRUMMING NOZZLE.  DRIVER HANDED DRUMMING NOZZLE TO RECEIVER AND WENT BACK TO TRACTOR TO START PTO PUMP.  RECEIVER WAS INSIDE OF ARCHER RUBBER BUILDING DRUMMING THE TOLUENE INTO 55 GALLON DRUMS.  APPROXIMATELY FIVE MINUTES INTO THE DELIVERY, ANOTHER ARCHER RUBBER EMPLOYEE CAME RUNNING OUTSIDE AND ASKED OUR DRIVER TO SHUT THE PTO PUMP OFF.  APPARENTLY THE RECEIVER DROPPED THE DRUMMING NOZZLE WITH THE VALVE OPEN CAUSING APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS OF PRODUCT TO SPILL ON TO THE CEMENT FLOOR IN THE BUILDING.  CLEAN UP AND DISPOSAL WAS TAKEN CARE OF BY ARCHER RUBBER. ARCHER RUBBER TOOK FULL RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE SPILL.

column168: ON MONDAY, AUGUST 27, 1990 UPS UNLOADER LONNIE BRIXEY NOTICED A PACKAGE LEAKING WHICH EMITTED A STRONG ODOR.  HE CALLED THIS TO THE ATTENTION OF HIS SUPERVISOR, BARRY BLISH.  THE LEAKING PACKAGE AND ANOTHER PACKAGE WHICH HAD BEEN SATURATED BY THE SPILL WERE PLACED INTO A UPS TOTE BOX AND SET ASIDE FOR VENTILATION NEAR AN OPEN OVERHEAD DOOR.  THE TIME WAS APPROXIMATELY 6:30 A.M.  BRIXEY WASHED HIS HANDS AND CONTINUED WORKING. THE PACKAGE WHICH LEAKED CONTAINED FOUR (4) BOTTLES OF FORMALDEHYDE SOLUTION.  ONE OF THE BOTTLES' CAP HAD APPARENTLY VIBRATED LOOSE IN TRANSIT AS THE PACKAGE WAS LEAKING IN THE UPS TRAILER BEFORE BEING HANDLED.  THE PACKAGE DID NOT HAVE THE PROPER HAZARDOUS CLASS LABEL (ORM-A) ON THE OUTER CARTON.  WITH NO IDENTIFICATION ON THE OUTER CARTON, THE UPS SUPERVISOR (BLISH) AND CENTER MANAGER (VERNON MUSKGROVE) WERE NOT IMMEDIATELY AWARE THAT THE SUBSTANCE WAS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. AT APPROXIMATELY 9:15 A.M., UPS DRIVER GERALD "RUSTY" GAROUTTE BECAME NAUSEATED WHILE MAKING A DELIVERY.  HE TRIED TO PHONE THE VINITA CENTER, BUT BLISH AND MUSKGROVE WERE NOT IN.  HE THEN TELEPHONED THE UPS TELEPHONE CENTER IN OKLAHOMA CITY TO REPORT HIS CONDITION AND THAT HE WAS GOING TO THE HOSPITAL IN MIAMI, OK. FOR TREATMENT.  ONE OF THE PACKAGES IN GAROUTTE'S VEHICLE HAD ALSO BEEN LEAKED ONTO, CAUSING THE DRIVER'S CONDITION.  HE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED.  UNLOADER BRIXEY REPORTED TO THE UPS DOCTOR, O.W. DEHART IN THE AFTERNOON.  HE ALSO WAS TREATED AND RELEASED.  UPS ACCOUNT EXECUTIVE JOHN VILLAREAL AND VINITA ASSISTANT FIRE CHIEF JIM BUTCHER ARRIVED AT THE UPS CENTER AT 1:00 P.M.  THEY CONTAINED AND NEUTRALIZED THE SUBSTANCE.  THE SHIPPER, CURTAIN MATHESON SCIENTIFIC IN LENEXA, KS WAS CONTACTED.  BILL JACKSON, SHIPPING MANAGER AT CMS WILL RETURN A CALL TO VERNON MUSKGROVE ON TUESDAY, AUGUST 28, FOR SPECIFIC DISPOSAL INSTRUCTIONS.  MUSKGROVE WILL DISPOSE AS HAZARDOUS WASTE IN A RCRA APPROVED FACILITY ON TUESDAY, AUGUST 28.  A PHONE CALL TO THE COUNTY HEALTH DEPARTMENT BY ASSISTANT FIRE CHIEF BUTCHER, WHO ALSO SERVES AS CRAIG COUNTY EMERGENCY PLANNING COMMITTEE CHAIRMAN, REVEALED THAT THE RCRA APPROVED SITE FOR THEIR AREA IS THE VINITA, OK. LANDFILL.  UPS EMPLOYEE BRIXEY RETURNED TO WORK OH TUESDAY, AUGUST 28.  UPS DRIVER GAROUTTE IS STILL EXPERIENCING HEADACHES AND WILL SEE THE DOCTOR AGAIN ON TUESDAY.

THE UNLOADING AREA WAS ON AN INCLINE.  THE FIRST THING I DID AFTER I GOT MY TRUCK SPOTTED WAS GO ON TOP OF THE TANK.  THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF PRODUCT AT THIS POINT.  I THOUGHT BECAUSE THE PRODUCT DID NOT SEEM TO BE AGAINST THE DOME OR THE RUPTURE DISC AREA THAT IT WOULD BE OK TO START THE AIR INTO THE TANK AND THEN OPEN THE VALVE, HOOKED THE DISCHARGE HOSE TO CUSTOMERS OUTLET AND TANK AND WAS ON MY WAY TO OPEN THE DISCHARGE VALVE. BEFORE I STARTED UP THE LADDER THE RUPTURE DISC BROKE, ALLOWING A FULL STREAM OF PRODUCT TO FLOW FROM IT'S HOSE.  RIGHT-A-WAY I SHUT THE AIR FLOW OFF AND OPENED THE DISCHARGE VALVE IN HOPES THAT THIS WOULD ALLOW THE PRODUCT TO STOP FLOWING FROM THE DISC HOSE.  THIS DID NOT STOP THE FLOW SO I SHUT THE DISCHARGE VALVE, RAN DOWN AND UNHOOKED THE HOSE AND PULLED THE TRUCK TO LEVEL GROUND, AT THIS POINT THE FLOW STOPPED.  IT IS MY BELIEF THAT THE RUPTURE DISC BROKE PREMATURELY.  THERE WAS ONLY 12 P.S.I. ON THE GAUGE.  THIS MAY HAVE OCCURED BECAUSE THE PRODUCT DID IN FACT GET IN THE DOME AREA.  I'M NOT SURE WHY THIS HAPPENED.  TO PREVENT THIS FROM OCCURING AGAIN #1-I WILL NOT APPLY AIR TO A TANK WITH A RUPTURE DISC IF THERE IS ANY POSSIBILITY OF PRODUCT GETTING TO IT, UNTIL I HAVE OPENED THE DISCHARGE VALVE.  #2-IF WE COULD PUT A VALVE IN THE LINE BEHIND THE RUPTURE DISC, IF THIS EVER HAPPENS AGAIN, AT LEAST THERE WOULD BE A WAY TO STOP THE FLOW OF PRODUCT FAST.

column168: ON AUGUST 27, 1990, FLIGHT 248 FROM SAN DIEGO TO MEMPHIS DIVERTED INTO LUBBOCK, TX DUE TO A STRONG CHEMICAL ODOR.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE FREIGHT (ONCE ON THE GROUND) IT AS DETERMINED THAT THE RESIN SOLUTION HAD LEAKED FROM THE LID.  THE CONTAINER HAD SOME MOISTURE (DROPLETS) ON THE TOP OF IT.  THERE WAS VERY LITTLE STANDING LIQUID.  WE FEEL THAT THE PRESSURE MUST HAVE BUILT UP ON THIS PACKAGE CAUSING LEAKAGE.  THE PRESSURE MUST HAVE CAUSED  AN AEROSOL FROM THE LID.  THIS CAUSED THE STRONG ODOR.  THE LOCAL FAA REPRESENTATIVE WAS NOTIFIED ALONG WITH THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CENTER, AND THE PACKAGE WAS OVERPACKED AND SENT ON. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND FAXED ENCLOSED MSDS ON THE SHIPPED MATERIAL.  THE SHIPPER STATED THAT CONTAINER WAS FIVE (5) GALLON DOT 17C AND THAT THERE WERE TWO (2) GALLONS OF OUTAGE.

column17: CARMAN J A TRUCKING CO INC
column168: NO FAILURE OF ANY COMPONENTS WAS INVOLVED IN THIS INCIDENT.  PLEASE REFER TO THE ATTACHED REPORT FOR THE SPECIFIC DETAILS. CERTIFIED #P 292 899 447 ATTACHED REPORT: ON THE MORNING OF TUESDAY AUGUST 7, 1990 AT +- 8:30AM, I RECEIVED A CALL FROM THOMAS SWERDAN WHO IS A SPILL INVESTIGATOR FOR N.Y.S. DEPT. OF ENVIROMENTAL CONSERVATION.  MR SWERDAN INFORMED ME THAT ONE OF OUR DRIVERS HAD A SPILL OF #2 FUEL OIL AT MECEHNICVILLE ELEMENTARY SCHOOL, AND HE ASKED IF WE WERE AWARE OF IT.  I SAID THAT NO ONE HAD REPORTED ANY SPILL OR OTHER PROBLEMS WITH THE DELIVERY TO CARMAN TRAUCKING.  WE THEN AGREED TO MEET AT THE SPILL SITE. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCHOOL, I FOUND A SHEEN OF OIL FLOATING ON SOME PUDDLES AND THAT SEVERAL PILES OF SAND HAD BEEN BROUGHT IN BY THE SCHOOL DISTRICT TO COVER SOME OF THE OIL AS WELL AS TO BLOCK OF THE STORM DRAINS FROM RECEIVING ANY FURTHER CONTAMIANTION RUN-OFF.  MR SWERDAN FROM DEC AND MYSELF THEN WENT DOWN ALONG THE RIVER TO WHERE THE STORM DRAIN EMPTIES OUT. THERE WAS A VISIBLE SHEEN OF OIL ALONG THE SHORE, BUT IT WAS SO THIN THAT WE WERE NOT ABLE TO ABSORB ANY OF IT.  I THEN PLACED AN OIL ABSORBING BOOM AND PADS AROUND THE STORM DRAIN OUTLET TO CATCH ANY FURTHER OIL THAT MIGHT COME OUT. IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT THE OIL WE WERE DELIVERING WAS LEFT OVER FROM A DELIVERY TO THE MECHANICVILLE HIGH SCHOOL.  THE SCHOOL HAD ORDERED TWO LOADS OF FUEL FOR THE HIGH SCHOOL, BUT THE SECOND LOAD WOULDN'T FIT SO THE SCHOOL SENT OUR DRIVER TO THE ELEMENTARY SCHOOL WITH THE BALANCE OF THE LOAD.  AFTER DELIVERY OF THE REMAINING PRODUCT OUR DRIVER WAS PREPARING TO LEAVE WHEN DICK (THE SCHOOL'S BOILERMAN), HOLLERED BACK UP TO THE DRIVER THAT ON HIS WAY BACK TO THE BOILERROOM HE HAD FOUND OIL ON THE LOWER FIELD. IT IS MY UNDERSTANDING THAT OUR DRIVER & DICK CLEANED UP ALL OIL THEY SAW AT THAT POINT. BUT NEITHER OUR DRIVER, BILL WHITEHOUSE, NOR THE SCHOOL'S EMPLOYEE NOTIFIED J.A. CARMAN TRUCKING OF ANY PROBLEMS WITH THE DELEIVERY AS THEY SHOULD HAVE. I BELEIVE THAT AFTER CLEANING UP THE OIL AND LEAVING, THE HEAVY RAINS CONTINUED TO FLUSH OIL OUT FROM CONTAMINATED SOIL AROUND THE STICK HOLE AND FLOATED IT OUT ONTO THE LOWER FIELD AND INTO THE STORM DRAINS WHERE IT WAS NOTICED BY BOATERS WHO CALLED CITY POLICE AND FIRE OFFICALS WHO NOTIFIED D.E.C.

column42: FILMS, NITROCELLULOSE BASE, GELATINE COATED (EXCEPT SCRAP)
column168: ON AUGUST 17, 1990 AT 1:30 PST ENSCO EMERGENCY COORDINATOR, DAVE VRSHEK, CONTACTED TRAVIS FINDLY AT HOME TO NOTIFY HIM THAT FINDLY CHEMICAL DISPOSAL'S  TRAILER ON ENSCO'S SITE IN EL DORADO, ARKANSAS WAS ON FIRE AND MR. VRSHEK REQUESTED INFORMATION REGARDING THE REACTIVE MATERIALS ON THE TRAILER.  THE FIRE WAS EXTINGUISHED BY ENSCO'S ON-SITE FIRE TEAM AND THE EL DORADO FIRE DEPARTMENT. THE MATERIAL WHICH STARTED THE FIRE WAS SUSPECTED TO BE NITROCELLULOSE-BASED MOVIE FILM GENERATED BY UCLA FILM ARCHIVES AND TRANSPORTED VIA MANIFEST NUMBER AR-458323.  TRAVIS FINDLY FLEW TO ARKANSAS THE NEXT MORNING AND ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AT 4:00 EST.  THE MATERIAL WAS CONFIRMED TO BE THE NITROCELLULOSE FILM.  UPON CONVERSATION WITH FINDLY CHEMICAL DISPOSAL OFFICE, IT WAS VERIFIED THAT THERE WERE MORE DRUMS FROM UCLA FILM ARCHIVES IN OUR YARD SCHEDULED FOR SHIPMENT TO ENSCO. UPON OPENING OF THE DOT 21C FIBER DRUMS, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE FILM WAS NOT IN THE MOVIE CANISTERS BUT WERE PACKED WITH WATER INSIDE OF PLASTIC TRASH BAGS.  THE FILM WAS TRANSFERRED TO METAL DRUMS DOT 17H AND PACKED UNDER WATER FOR RESHIPMENT BACK TO UCLA FILM ARCHIVES.  IT WAS RECOMMENDED THAT THE PROVISIONS OF 49 CFR SECTION 173.177 MUST BE FOLLOWED AND, IN THE EVENT THAT THE FILM WAS NOT ABLE TO BE SHIPPED IN THE FILM CANISTERS, SECTION 173.184 MUST BE USED TO SHIP THE FILM. ENCLOSED ARE ALL THE MANIFESTS WHICH WERE ON THE TRAILER, BUT ONLY MANIFEST NUMBER AR-458323 INVOLVED DRUMS WHICH WERE SIGNIFICANTLY DAMAGED AND UNABLE TO PROCESS AT ENSCO.  THERE WERE SEVEN MANIFESTS WHICH WERE RETURNED TO THE GENERATORS: AR-443077, AR-443078, AR-443081, AR-450897, AR-458325, AR-449440 AND AR-458328.  THESE DRUMS WERE RETURNED TO HELP ENSCO SATISFY THEIR PUBLIC RELATIONS FOLKS AND EASE THE BURDEN ON THEIR STORAGE FACILITY.

INNER PACKAGE BROKE DURING SORTING PRIOR TO TRANSLOAD TO ANOTHER FLIGHT. CONTENTS INSIDE OF PACKAGE CONSISTED OF FOUR (4) ONE GALLON GLASS JUGS. SPECIFICATION PACKAGE WAS NOT USED.  THE PACKAGE DID NOT CONTAIN ANY MARKINGS OR LABELS TO IDENTIFY THE CHEMICAL AS A DANGEROUS GOODS.  A SHIPPER DECLARATION WAS NOT OFFERED TO FEDERAL EXPRESS BY SHIPPER.  FEDERAL EXPRESS REPORTED THIS INCIDENT TO THE FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINISTRATION AS A HIDDEN DISCREPANCY.

ANHYDROUS AMMONIA TANK CAR GATX 97372 WAS DELIVERED TO THE LAROCHE INDUSTRIES RIVERDALE FACILITY AT APPROXIMATELY 1500 HOURS ON AUGUST 30, 1990. PLANT PERSONNEL REMOVED ONE PLUG FROM THE LIQUID DISCHARGE VALVE AND ONE PLUG FROM A VAPOR DICHARGE VALVE.  TWO UNLOADING PIPES WERE INSTALLED AND TIGHTENED SECURELY.  THESE PIPES WERE THEN IN TURN SECURED WITH STEEL CAPS.  THE ACTUAL DISCHARGE VALVES WERE NOT ADJUSTED DURING THIS OPERATION. AT APPROXIMATELY 2345 HOURS, NOTIFICATION WAS RECEIVED THAT AN AMMONIA LEAK HAD DEVELOPED.  THE PLANT SUPERVISOR, WITH ASSISTANCE FROM THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT, WAS ABLE TO TIGHTEN ALL THREE VALVES ON THE TANK CAR AND STOP THE LEAK. TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS, ALL VALVES, CAPS, PLUGS AND PIPES WILL BE TIGHTENED AND CHECKED FOR TIGHTNESS WITH A WRENCH OR APPROPRIATE TOOL. THIS RELEASE WAS REPORTED TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (INCIDENT #37741).

UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD MANAGER YARD AND INDUSTRY OPERATIONS, BOB JONES, REPORTED THAT TANK CAR IMCX 2820, RESIDUE, ALST CONTAINED ANHYDROUS AMMONIA, WAS GIVING OFF A STRONG AMMONIA ODOR IN TRACK 104.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED TO TRACK 206, WHERE IT WAS INSPECTED BY UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD SPECIAL AGENT0-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, ARLA ROQUET.  IMC REPRESENTATIVE WAYNE WILLIS, RAIL FLEET SPECIALIST, WAS ADVISED OF THE CAR STATUS THROUGH CHEMTREC.  MANAGER OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS EMERGENCY RESPONSE, BOB STINE, RESPONDED TO THE SCENE, PER REQUEST, WHEN IT INITIALLY APPEARED TO BE A DEFECTIVE SAFETY VAVLE.  UPON FURTHER INSPECTION, IT WAS NOTED THAT THE LEAK SOURCE CAME FROM BETWEEN THE MANWAY COVER PLATE AND THE MANWAY NOZZLE.  ALL ACCESSIBLE BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED.  THE LEAK WAS REDUCED, ALLOWING THE CAR TO BE MOVE TO TANK LINING AND RAIL CAR REPAIR, A LOCAL REPAIR FACILITY, FOR PERMANAENT REPAIRS.  CAR WAS DELIVERED TO THE REPAIR FACILITY ON AUGUST 22, 1990, WITHOUT DURTHER INCIDENT.

MARTIN CAR SENIOR SAFETY OFFICER, EDDY BULLOCK AND HIS ASSISTANTS, ARRIVED 1100HOURS, 08-16-90, AND OFFLOADED 9,450 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT AT 1340 HOURS.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 4:30 AM ON THURSDAY AUG 23  CHEMLINK DRIVER JOHN DUNBAR WAS DRIVING THE COMPANY 1984 FREIGHTLINER FLATBED (LOADED WITH FIVE 550-GALLON TOTE TANKS OF HS-9767) WEST ON HIGHWAY 16, ON HIS WAY TO THE WILBURTON AREA, AND NOTICED LIQUID LEAKING FROM HIS TRUCK WHEN A VEHICLE CAME UP BEHIND HIM AND FLASHED ITS HEADLIGHTS.  DUNBAR IMMEDIATELY PULLED OVER AND SECURED HIS VEHICLE, AND SAW THE PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE FIRST TOTE TANK CLOSEST TO THE CAB.  HE FLAGGED DOWN A PASSING MOTORIST HEADING EAST BACK INTO BEGGS, AND ASKED THE DRIVER TO NOTIFY THE POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENTS, AND HAVE THEM CALL KEN WILDBUR, JR.. DUNBAR REMAINED WITH HIS VEHICLE. WILDBUR CALLED ME AT APPROXIMATELY 5:00 AM., AND NOTIFIED T. CHILDERS AND D. CLARK, AND ASKED THEM TO BEGIN PREPARING FOR A RESPONSE TO THE SPILL.  BEGGS POLICE AND FIRE OFFICIALS NOTIFIED THE STATE DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND STATE HIGHWAY DEPARTMENT AND BEGAN ISOLATING THE APPROXIMATE 4-MILE STRETCH OF HIGHWAY 16 WHERE THE CHEMICAL HAD BEEN SPILLED.  THE LEAK BEGAN WTH THE FAILURE OF A PVC 2" NIPPLE BETWEEN THE STAINLESS MOUNTING PLATE FOR THE UNLOADING VALVE ASSEMBLY AND THE END VALVE ITSELF, AND HAD BEGUN APPROXIMATLEY 1 MILE EAST OF BEGGS, CONTINUING THROUGH TOWN AND 2 MILES WEST.  DUNBAR WAS UNABLE TO SEE THE LEAKING LIQUID IN THE DARK, AND DID NOT REALIZE HE HAD LEAK UNTIL THE PASSING VEHICLE FLASHED ITS LIGHTS.  CHEMLINK RESPONSE PERSONNEL WERE ASSEMBLED AT THE PLANT BY 6:00 AM., AND DEPARTED SAND SPRINGS AT 7:00.  T. CHILDERS, J. PETERSON, T. BEASON, J. VANN. AND J. HUGO RESPONDED WITH TWO TRUCKS, THE ERT TRAILER, AND AN EMPTY TOTE TANK AND TRANSFER PUMP TO SECURE ANY PRODUCT REMAINING IN THE LEAKING TANK.  ... THE REMAINING 150 GALLONS IN THE TANK WERE TRANSFERRED TO THE EMPTY TOTE TANK, POOLED WATER/PRODUCT MIXTURES ALONG THE SPILL ROUTE WERE CLEANED UP AND PLACED INTO OPEN TOP DRUMS, AND THE SPILLED PRODUCT ON AND UNDER THE TRUCK WAS CLEANED UP AND THEN WASHED DOWN BY A FIRE TRUCK.  MARVIN BOATRIGHT, ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES DIVISION, OKLAHOMA STATE DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH, RECOMMENDED THAT THE DRUMMED MATERIAL BE TRANFERRED TO THE OKMULGEE COUNTY LANDFILL IN MORRIS....CAUSE OF THE ACCIDENT: A 2" PVC NIPPLE BETWEEN THE STAINLESS STEEL MOUNTING PLATE AND STAINLESS STEEL UNLOADING VALVE FAILED, DUE TO VIBRATION OR STRESS DURING PREVIOUS UNLOADING ACTIVITES.  TWO MORE TOTE TANKS USED FOR HS 9767 WERE ALSO FOUND WITH PVC UNLOADING VALVE ASSEMBLY COMPONENTS, AND HAVE BEEN TAKEN OUT OF SERVICE.  RECOMMENDATIONS:  1. PVC COMPONENTS SHOULD NOT BE UTILIZED IN ANY PORTION OF THE UNLOADING VALVE ASSEMBLY ON TOTE TANKS FOR CORROSIVE SERVICE. 2. UNLOADING VALVE ASSEMBLIES SHOULD BE SUPPORTED IF POSSIBLE TO RELIEVE STRESS FROM UNLOADING ACTIVITIES.  3. DRIVERS SHOULD BE PROVIDED WITH THE MOST CURRENT MSDS FOR PRODUCTS THEY ARE TRANSPORTING. 4. A CELLULAR PHONE OR OTHER MOBILE TELEPHONE SHOULD BE ACQUIRED FOR COMPANY PERSONNEL INVOLVED IN OFF-SITE SPILL RESPONSE.

FLIGHT 2974 RETURNED BACK TO GREEN BAY, WHEN CAPTAIN ADVISED OPERATIONS OF A STRONG ODOR COMING FROM THE FORWARD CARGO HOLD.  UPON UNLOADING OF BAGGAGE A BLACK CANVAS LINED BAG HAD A STRONG ODOR.  AFTER OPENING THE BAG A 1/4 OUNCE BOTTLE WAS FOUND BROKEN IN THE BOTTOM OF THE BAG.  PACKED IN THE CHECKED BAG WERE ALSO 2 BOWLING BALLS, ACE BANDAGE, TOWEL, AS WELL AS 2 MORE BOTTLES OF THE SKIN PROTECTOR.  EACH BOTTLE WAS MARKED FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  THE SPILL WAS CONFINED TO THE INSIDE OF THE BAG.  THE CUSTOMER, LOUIS RINDNER, WAS CONTACTED ABOUT HIS CHECKED BAG TO CONFIRM THE CONTENTS OF THE BAG.  HE DID CONFIRM THE CONTENTS AND BAG TO BE HIS.

column42: MATCHES, SAFETY (BOOK, CARD OR STRIKE ON BOX
column168: A PIECE OF CHECKED BAGGAGE BELONGING TO DR. AMEDEO PELLEGRINI WAS OBSERVED TO BE SMOKING DURING THE LOADING PROCESS.  THE BAG WAS LOCKED WITH A KEY LOCK.  THE PASSENGER WAS PAGED ONBOARD THE AIRCRAFT AND WAS ESCORTED ONTO THE RAMP AREA AND UNLOCKED THE BAG.  THE BAG WAS INSPECTED AND A BOX OF KITCHEN MATCHES WAS FOUND TO HAVE IGNITED.  THE BAG WAS REMOVED FROM THE FLIGHT AND THE FAA WAS ADVISED.  THEY ALSO INSPECTED THE BAG AND TOOK PHOTOS. THE BAG WAS LATER FORWARDED TO JFK ON A LATER TWA FLIGHT.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES TO ANY TWA PERSONNEL OR EQUIPMENT.

column168: ON AUGUST 31,1990 AT 1320, RICHARD GORECKI, A MOBIL DRIVER WAS UNLOADING GASOLINE AT A MOBIL STATION IN COMMACK, NEW YORK.  AS RITCHIE WAS DROPPING THE UNLEADED GASOLINE, A TRUCK EXITING THE STATION RAN OVER THE HOSE. THIS BROKE THE FITTING ON THE TANK, DISLOGDED THE HOSE AND CAUSED GASOLINE TO ESCAPE.  THE DRIVER OF THE MOBIL TRUCK WAS STANDING BY HIS TRUCK WHEN THIS OCCURED AND IMMEDIATELY DISCONTINUED THE TRANSFER.  THE GASOLINE ROLLED DOWN A HILL AND WENT INTO A LATCH BASIN ON THE STATIONS PROPERTY. APPROXIMATELY 35 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RECOVERED FROM THE BASIN BY UNICO, OUR SPILL CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR.

column168: UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, H W RODABOUGH, WAS NOTIFIED AT 0520 HOURS REGARDING THE INJURY OF THREE EMPLOYEES AT STOCKTON, CALIFORNIA.  INJURIES RESULTED FROM A SPILL OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FROM TANK CAR CALX 1009.  THERE WAS A RELEASE FROM THE DOME OF THE CAR WHILE CAR WAS BEING SWITCHED.  INSPECTION BY MR. RODABOUGH DETERMINED THAT THE SPILL WAS CAUSED BY AN IMPROPERLY SECURED MANWAY COVER.  THREE BOLTS ON THE RIGHT SIDE WERE FOUND TO BE WITHIN THE REQUIRED LIMITS. THE GASKET CHECKED AND FOUND TO BE SERVICEABLE, AND REPAIRS WERE COMPLETED BY TIGHTENING THE EYE BOLTS.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO THE SOUTHERN PACIFIC AT 1630 HOURS.  ADDITIONAL DEFICIENCIES WITH THE CAR WERE AS FOLLOWS: 1) THE SAFETY VALVE TEST WAS PAST DUE, AND 2) BILLING CALLED FOR THE CAR TO BE PLACARDED FLAMMABLE WITH THE UN NUMBER 9189.  MR. RODABOUGH CONTACTED MRS. SUE VEDANTHEM, THE ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEER AT SOLVENT SERVICE, AND INFORMED HER OF THE PAST DUE SAFETY VALVE INSPECTION DATE, THE INCONSISTENT INFORMATION ON THE WAYBILL, AND THE PLACARDING ON THE CAR.  SHE IDENTIFIED THE COMMODITY AS 1% SOLVENT AND 99% WATER, A BY-PRODUCT OF A STRIPPING OPERATION IN THEIR PLANT.  CONTACT WAS ALSO MADE WITH MIKE CRESCO, CUSTOMER SERVICE-ST. LOUIS, REGARDING THE INCONSISTENT BILLING AND ITS CAUSE.

UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, D.W. ALM, WAS NOTIFIED AT 1830 HOURS, AUGUST 13, 1990, OF LEAKING TRAILER APLU 970738 AT THE UNION PACIFIC INTERMODAL TRAILER FACILITY, OAKLAND, CALIFORNIA.  MR. ALM TRAVELED TO OAKLAND AND AT 1000 HOURS, AUGUST 14, 1990, FOUND A 5 GALLON DRUM OF FLAMMABLE LIQUID LEAKING IN TRAILER APLU 970738.  DRUM HAD BEEN DENTED AT SOME EARLIER DATE AND THE METAL FAILED AT THE DAMAGED AREA ON THE FIRST ROLLING HOOP.  LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED IN AN OVERPACK DRUM ALONG WITH TOWELS WHICH WERE USED TO WIPE UP SPILLED COMMODITY AND REPACKED INSIDE THE SAME TRAILER.  NO LOAD SHIFT WAS EVIDENT AND THE TRAILER WAS PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED.  TRAILER WAS RELEASED AT 0900 HOURS, AUGUST 15, 1990.  SHIPPING PAPERS WERE CORRECT.

column168: UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, H.W. RODABOUGH, WAS NOTIFIED BY UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD CHIEF CLERK, KENT MORBY, THAT TANK CAR KCCX 2230 WAS REPORTEDLY LEAKING AND WAS SPOTTED ON THE CAB TRACK WAITING FOR REPAIR.  MR. MORBY FURTHER REPORTED THAT ONE SWITCHMAN HAD BEEN TRANSPORTED TO THE HOSPITAL AFTER HAVING BEEN SPLASHED WITH ACID. MR. RONALD WILLIAM THORUM WAS TREATED AND RELEASED, SUFFERING FROM MINOR BURNS TO THE HANDS AND SOME DISCOMFORT IN THE EYES.  MR. THORUM DID NOT HAVE ANY LOST WORK DAYS DUE TO THIS INJURY. INSPECTION OF CAR KCCX 2230 BY MR. RODABOUGH DETERMINED THAT THE LEAKING CONDITION WAS THE RESULT OF A MISAPPLIED FILL HOLE GASKET.  GASKET WAS OFF SET AND FLIPPED UP ON ONE SIDE EXPOSING APPROXIMATELY FOUR INCHES, ALLOWING THE CAR TO LEAK. CONDITION WAS MITIGATED AS FOLLOWS:  THE FILL HOLE AND LID WERE CLEANED AND WIPED DRY AND THE GASKET WAS CLEANED AND REAPPLIED.  THE LID WAS THEN CLOSED WITH SPECIAL ATTENTION TO THE FIT OF THE GASKET AND SECURED.

column168: WHILE TRAIL WAS DEPARTING NORTH LITTLE ROCK, TRAIN CREW NOTED TANK CAR TGAX 131408 LEAKING LIQUID FROM THE TOP OF CAR.  UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD MANAGER OF YARD AND INDUSTRY OPERATIONS, RICK PENNINGTON, CONTACTED UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, C.L. HILL. MR. HILL'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THE MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS OUT OF LINE ALLOWING PHOSPHORIC ACID TO LEAK WHEN CAR WAS MOVED.  GASKET WAS ALIGNED PROPERLY, CAR WAS SECURED AND ALLOWED TO CONTINE TO DESTINATION. MR. HILL CONTACTED CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER AND INFORMED THEM OF THIS INCIDENT.

UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, T.H. SMITH WAS ADVISED THAT RAILCAR IORY 3066 WAS LOADED WITH 95 30-GALLON PLASTIC DRUMS AND 500 100-LB. BAGS OF FIRE CLAY.  THE DRUMS WERE POSITIONED IN BOTH ENDS OF THE RAILCAR AND SOME BAGS WERE STACKED ON TOP OF THE DRUMS. THE REMAINDER OF THE BAGS WERE POSITIONED IN THE MIDDLE OF THE RAILCAR. DUE TO SHIFTING CARGO, SEVEN OF THE A-END DRUMS BECAME MISSHAPEN CAUSING THE BUNGS TO LOOSEN.  MOVEMENT SPILLAGE RAN DOWN THE SIDES OF THE DRUM AND LEAKED THROUGH THE FLOOR. MR. SMITH REPOSITIONED PART OF THE LOAD TO RELIEVE THE STRESSED DRUMS AND THE BUNGS WERE REPLACED.  ONE OF THE SEVEN BUNGS HAD TO BE EPOXIED INTO PLACE DUE TO THE THREADS ON THE BUNG BEING DAMAGED.  A NEUTRALIZING SOLUTION WAS APPLIED TO THE OUTSIDE OF THE CAR WHERE THE SPILL WAS EVIDENT AND A SORBENT WAS BROADCAST TO THE INTERIOR OF THE CAR TO CONTAIN ANY SPILL THAT MAY HAVE REMAINED IN THE CAR.

STINE, OF A LEAKING TANK CAR OF PHOSPHORIC ACID AT THE YERMO, CALIFORNIA RAIL YARD. INSPECTION BY MR. ALM DETERMINED THAT THE RUPTURE DISC HAD BURST ON TANK CAR CHVX 785017.  MR. UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, H.W. RODABOUGH, WAS NOTIFIED BY UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT, H.L. JACOBSEN, THAT TANK CAR UTLX 14682 WAS SPOTTED ON THE WEST LEG OF THE Y AT GREEN RIVER, WYOMING AND WAS LEAKING.  INSPECTION BY MR. RODABOUGH DETERMINED THAT THE CAR HAD FAILED AT A POINT APROXIMATELY ONE FOOT TOWARD THE B END OF THE CAR AT ABOUT THE FIVE O'CLOCK POSITION.  THE HOLE WAS APPROXIMATELY THE SIZE OF A QUARTER AND HAD BEEN PATCHED BY WORKMEN FROM THE CHEVRON PLANT WHERE THE SHIPMENT HAD ORIGINATED.  APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF 52% PHOSPHORIC ACID HAD SPILLED TO THE GROUND AT THIS LOCATION. MITIGATION EFFORTS ON BEHALF OF THE CHEVRON PERSONNEL INCLUDED A DIKE AT THE EAST END OF THIS SPILL TO PREVENT ANY OF THE PRODUCT FROM ENTERING THE DRAINAGE DITCH LOCATED ABOUT 20 FEET EAST OF THIS LOCATION.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH CHEVRON TO TRANSLOAD THE REMAINING PRODUCT.  INSPECTION OF THE YARD DETERMINED THAT THERE WAS A LARGE SPILL AREA WHERE THE CAR HAD PREVIOUSLY BEEN SPOTTED.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO REMOVE THE CONTAMINATION FROM THE YARD.  CLEANUP OPERATIONS COMMENCED ON AUGUST 20 AND WERE CONCLUDED ON AUGUST 23, 1990.  JOHN BROWNING OF CHEVRON CHEMICAL AND JACK ZIMMERMAN OF THE GREEN RIVER FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE PRESENT FOR THE CLEANUP.

UPRR MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS EMERGENCY RESPONSE R. M. STINE WAS NOTIFIED BY CAR FOREMAN THAT CONTAINER OOLU 411323 PLACARDED CORROSIVE WAS ON TRACK 306 AND SHOWED AN INDICATION OF A LEAK AT LEFT REAR CONTAINER DOOR.  INSPECTION BY MR. STINE DETERMINED THAT THE LOAD CONSISTED OF 16-GALLON CAPACITY DRUMS ON PALLETS AND WERE SECURED WITH "TY-GUARD". AT THE BASE OF THE REAR PALLETS THE SHIPPER HAD PLACED SECTIONS OF SORBENT BOOM WHICH HAD ABSORBED MOST OF THE LEAKAGE.  LABEL ON ONE LEAKING CONTAINER READ "WASTE COMPOUND CLEANING LIQUID.  CORROSIVE MATERIAL NA 1760 EPA F002".  THIS DRUM HAD A PIN HOLE JUST BELOW THE BOTTOM ROLLING HOOP.  THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKAGE FROM THE DRUM AT THE TIME OF HIS INPECTION, INDICATING THAT LIQUID WAS BELOW THE PIN HOLE,  THE CAR WAS SET TO THE RAMP FOR LOAD ADJUSTMENT AND FURTHER INSPECTION.  THE SHIPPER AND RIEDEL ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES WERE CONTACTED.  ON 08/28/90 THE CONTAINER WAS UNLOADED AND ALL DRUMS WERE INSPECTED.  ONE ADDITIONAL DRUM WAS LEAKING FROM A PIN HOLE JUST BELOW THE BOTTOM ROLLING HOOP.  BOTH LEAKING DRUMS WERE PLACED IN OVERPACKS.  THE FLOOR DRY USED ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER UNDER THE ONE DRUM BY REAR DOORS AND THE PROTECTIVE CLOTHING WORN BY THE WORKERS WERE PLACED IN AN OVERPACK DRUM AND PLACED AT THE REAR OF THE LOAD FOR SHIPMENT.  AFTER RELOADING, SPD TRANSFER SERVICE WAS CONTACTED AND PLACED BLOCKING ON THE LOAD PRIOR TO BEING RELEASED.

column168: UPRR MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS EMERGENCY RESPONSE R.M. STINE WAS NOTIFIED THAT CAR WAS NOTED HAVING A VAPOR EMITTING FROM THE TOP.  AS MR STINE WAS OUT OF TOWN, HE CONTACTED MR. A.D. MATY, SHIEF INSPECTOR AAR BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES, WHO RESPONDED. INSPECTION BY MR MATY DETERMINED THAT THE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE BLIND FLANGE WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED ACCOUNT THE NUTS FOR THE FOUR BOLTS WERE MERELY THREADED ONTO THE BOLTS, AND NOT TIGHTNED THE LENGTH OF THE BOLT.  THE NUTS WERE TIGHTENED, THUS SECURING THE LEAK.  THE SAFETY VENT FRANGIBLE DISC WAS INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE INTACT.  SHIPMENT WAS CONTRARY TO SECTIONS 173.29 (C) (1) AND (2) AND (E); 174.9 (B); AND 174.67(K), TITLE 49 CFR, FOR FAILURE TO PROPERLY SECURE A TANK CAR AFTER UNLAODING THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS CONTAINED THEREIN.  A COPY OF MR. MATY'S REPORT WAS FURNISHED TO BUREAU INSEPCTOR R.J EWOLDT FO RHIS HANDLING WITH THE SHIPPER.

UPRR MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS EMERGENCY RESPONSE R.M. STINE WAS CONTACTED BY UPRR YARDMASTER ROD BUDIMLJA, WICHITA, ADVISING THAT CREWS REPORTED A STRONG ODOR OF AMMONIA NEAR A CUT OF EIGHT LOADED AMMONIA CARS. MR. STINE AND MR. A.D. MATY, CHIEF INSPECTOR AAR BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES, MADE INSPECTION AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT CAR UTLX 80654 HAD VAPOR ESCAPING FROM THE BASE OF THE "A" END LIQUID VALVE.  MR. STINE SECURED NUTS ON VALVE BASE AND LEAK STOPPED.  MR. STINE NOTIFIED MR. CARL REYNOLDS AT CHEMTREC AND TRAIN MANAGEMENT-OMAHA.  HE ALSO NOTIFIED MR. JOHN GOEBEL AT FARMLAND.

UPRR MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS EMERGENCY RESPONSE R. M. STINE WAS CONTACTED BY DUTY YARDMASTER AT WICHITA ADVISING THAT CREWS REPORTED STRONG ODOR OF AMMONIA IN THE AREA OF SEVERAL TANK CARS INCLUDING GATX 97435.  MR. STINE IN COMPANY WITH MR. A.D. MATY, CHIEF INSPECTOR AAR BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES, INSPECTED THE CAR.  HIS INSEPCTION DETERMINED THERE WAS A VAPOR LEAK AT THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  THE VALVE WAS A "REGO A 7890-16"; THE "O" RING HAD BLOWN OUT, AND HAD A SECTION MISSING.  ATTEMPTS TO REPLACE THE "O" RING AND TIGHTEN THE RETAINER WERE UNSUCCESSFUL.  MR STINE NOTIFIED MR. CARL REYNOLDS AT CHEMTREC AND TRAIN MANAGEMENT-OMAHA. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH MR. JOHN GOEBEL OF FARMLAND INDUSTRIES TO TRANSFER LADING TO TANK TRUCKS.  FIRST TRUCK ARRIVED ON SITE AT 0530 HOURS, AUGUST 31, 1990.  OFF-LOADING WAS COMPLETED AT 1455 HOURS.  BAD ORDER CAR WAS STENCILLED "LEAKY TANK DO NOT LOAD UNTIL REPAIRED", AS REQUIRED.

UPRR MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS EMERGENCY RESPONSE R.M. STINE WAS NOTIFIED BY MR. RUSS VASSER THAT CREWS WERE REPORTING A STRONG ODOR OF AMMONIA IN YARDS NEAR TRACK 105.  IN CHECKING REPORT MR. STINE LOCATED THE SOURCE AS CAR GATX 55466.  INSPECTION BY MR.  STINE DETERMINED THAT THE VAPOR VALVE AND PORT PLUG WERE LOOSE.  HE ALSO NOTED THE SAMPLE LINE PLUG WAS LOOSE, SLIP TUBE GAUGE VALVE PLUG, AND BOTH LIQUID LINE PLUGS WERE LOOSE.  HE SECURED ALL FITTINGS AND RELEASED CAR FOR MOVEMENT.  MS SUSAN TRACY AT CHEMTREC AND TRAIN MANAGEMENT-OMAHA WERE NOTIFEID.  MR. STINE ALS HANDLED EXCEPTIONS WITH MR. JOHN GOEBEL OF FARMLAND INDUSTRIES.

UPRR MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS EMERGENCY RESPONSE R.M. STINE WAS CONTACTED BY MR. RUSS VASSER WHO ADVISED THAT CREWS WERE REPORTING A VERY STRONG ODOR OF AMMONIA INT HE AREA OF SEVERAL TANK CARS ON TRACK 105, NEFF YARD.  INSPECTION BY MR STINE DETERMINED THERE WAS VAPOR LEAK FROM THE AREA OF THE PARKING GLAND NUT ON SLIP TUBE GAUGING DEVICE.  MR. STINE TIGHTENED NUT WHICH SECURED LEAK.  MS. SUSAN TRACY AT CHEMTREC AND TRAIN MANAGEMENT-OMAHA WERE NOTIFIED. INFORMATION WAS ALSO FURNISHED TO MR. JOHN GOEBEL AT FARMLAND INDUSTRIES.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Water Damage
column168: UPRR MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS EMERGENCY RESPONSE R.M. STINE WAS NOTIFIED BY MR. J.L. SCHINZE THAT PRODUCT WAS NOTED SPLASHING FROM CAR DURING SWITCHING.  INPSECTION BY MR STIEN DETERMINED THAT THE FRANGIBLE DISC IN IN SAFETY VENT HAD BURST.  DISC WAS A "BS&B" 100 LB TEST DISC. MR. STINE REPLACED WITH LIKE DISC AND RINSED SIDES OF CAR PRIOR TO RELEASING FOR MOVEMENT.  MS. SUSAN TRACY AT CHEMTREC AND TRAIN MANAGEMENT-OMAHA WERE NOTIFIED.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Water Damage
column168: UPRR MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS EMERGENCY RESPONSE R.M. STINE WAS NOTIFIED BY UPRR YARDMASTER AT WICHITA THAT CREWS REPORTED PRODUCT SPLASHING FROM VENT PIPE ON CAR DURING SWITCHING.  AS MR. STINE WAS OUT OF TOWN, HE CONTACTED KEITH TOONE OF VULCAN MATERILAS WHO AGREED TO RESPOND. INSPECTION BY MR.  TOONE DETERMINED THE FRANGIBLE DISC INSAFETY VENT HAD BURST.  DISC WAS AN "OSECO" 100 PSI DISC.  MR. TOONE REPLACED WITH LIKE DISC AND RELEASED CAR FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT.  MR. JOE MALAZZO OF CHEMTREC AND TRAIN MANAGEMENT-OMAHA WERE NOTIFIED.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Water Damage
column168: UPRR MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS EMERGENCY RESPONSE R.M. STINE WAS NOTIFIED BY UPRR YARDMASTER AT WICHITA, KANSAS THAT CREWS REPORTED PRODUCT WAS SPLASHING FROM THE TOP OF CAR DURING SWITCHING.  AS MR STINE WAS OUT OF TOWN, CONTACT WAS MADE WITH MR. A.D. MATY, CHIEF INSPECTOR AAR BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES, AND HE RESPONDED. INSPECTION BY MR. MATY DETERMINED THAT FRANGIBLE DISC IN SAFETY VENT HAD BURST.  DISC WAS AN "OSECO" 100LB TEST DISC.  MR. MATY REPLACED WITH LIKE DISC AND RELEASED THE CAR FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: MR A.D. MATY, CHEIF INSPECTOR AAR BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVE, RECIEVED A REPORT FROM UPRR SENOIR SPECIAL AGAENT D.J. GISH THAT DIESEL SHOP EMPLOYEES HAD BEEN EXPOSED TO VAPORS FROM AN UNKNOWN SORUCE WHILE FUELING A LOCOMOTIVE AT NEFF YARD.  INSPECTION BY MR. MATY DEVELOPED THAT CAR DCBX 237 WAS BELIEVED TO BE LEAKING THE AFTERNEOON OF JULY 31, LEAKAGE EXCEPT FOR SOME EVIDENCE ON THE MANWAY NOZZLE.  THE MANWAY COVER WAS OPENED, REVEALING AN ASBESTOS GASKET.  THE MANWAY EYEBOLTS WERE LESS THAN FULL WRENCH TIGHT; AND, THE GASKET HAD BEEN CUT AND OVELAPPED TO FIT THE DIAMETER OF THE MANWAY COVER.  THE GASKET WAS REPOSITIONED AND THE MANWAY COVER RETIGHTENED. AT APPROXIMATELY 1030 HOURS, AUGUST 2, 1990, MR. MATY AGAIN RECEIVED ADVICE THAT ODOR WAS AGIAN EVIDENT AROUND CAR DCBX 237.  THE OVELAPPED ASBESTOS GASKET WAS REPLACED WITH A FIBER GASKET.  TANK WAS OBSERVED TO BE BUILDING INTERNAL PRESSURE AS EVIDENCED BY VAPOR ESCAPING WHEN THE VACCUM RELIEF VALVE WAS DEPRESSED, INDICATING THAT TANKS WAS VAPOR TIGHT.  CAR WAS RELEASED AT 1215 HOURS FOR CONTINUED TRANSPORTATION.

DRIVER WAS MAKING A DELIVERY OF FUEL OIL AT A RESIDENT CUSTOMER'S HOSE AND THE HOSE BROKE OUT OF THE NOZZLE AND 8 GALLONS WAS SPRAYED ONTO HIS SHRUBS.  THE SHRUBS WERE REMOVED AND REPLACED, BUT NO SOIL WAS CONTAMINATED SO A CLEANUP CONTRACTOR WAS NOT NEEDED.  WE FEEL THERE WAS A FAULTY CONNECTION BETWEEN THE NOZZLE AND THE HOSE.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Water Damage
column168: ON 08/24/90 SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERAILS (SSA/HM) DENNIS ALM WAS NOTIFIED BY MANAGER TRAIN OPERATION (MTO) AL WALLACE THAT CAR GATX 55797 WAS LEAKING IN THE STOCKTON RAIL YARD.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED.  SSA/HM ALM'S INSPECTION DETERMINED A SMALL VAPOR LEAK THAT WAS COMING FROM AROUND THE MANWAY NOZZLE UNDER THE COVER PALTE.  A STRIPPED MANWAY COVER BOLT WAS ALSO FOUND.  CHEMTREC AND FARMLAND INDUSTRIES REPRESENTATIVE  (JOHN GOBEL) WERE NOTIFIED AND JOHN GOBEL CONTACTED CALIFORNIA RAILCAR REPAIR, STOCKTON, CA.  CALIFORNIA RAILCAR REPAIR DETERMINED THE LEAK WAS DUE TO THE LOOSE MANWAY COVER BOLT AND THAT THE TANK NEEDED TO BE OFFLOADED BEFORE REPAIRS COULD BE MADE. SSA/HM ALM BEGAN ARRANGING WITH CAL AMMONIA (BOB SMITH) FOR OFFLOADING. BOB SMITH EXAMINED THE TANK CAR AND COULD FIND NO LEAKS.  TANK CAR AT THAT TIME WAS RELEASED TO SOUTHERN PACIFIC RAILROAD AND TRANSPORTATION 5 MILES TO DESTINATION WHERE IT WAS OFFLOADED AND RETURNED HOME FOR REPAIR.

UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD DISPATCHER J DAVIS REPORTED THAT TANK CAR RCRX 1063 WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP DIP PIPE INLET.  DOWELL REPRESENTATIVE JEFF SCHULTE, MONAHANS, TEXAS, RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND REMOVED THE BLIND FLANGE FROM THE LIQUID LINE, RELIEVING THE PRESSURE.  THE CAUSE WAS DETERMINED TO BE A BUILG UP OF PRESSURE DUE TO THE RISE IN AMBIENT OF SODA ASH.  UNION PACIFIC MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS (DAVE LANCASTER) WAS ON SCENE WHILE THE INCIDENT WAS CORRECTED.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED.

column168: DISTRICT SPECIAL AGENT BOB PICHLER WAS NOTIFIED TO TANK CAR TGAX 141568 LEAKING FROM THE TOP.  SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL (SSA/HM)STU WHITED WAS OUT OF THE AREA AND BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES DANIEL M. HEALY WAS REQUESTED TO RESPOND.  MR. HEALY'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THE SAFETY VENT DISC WAS RUPTURED.  RUPTURE DISC WAS REPLACED WITH SAME AND CAR WAS RELEASED.
